subtitle: Hello, I'm Jeffrey Mishlove. I'm just back
from the Psychotronics conference in
Chicago. I may seem a little weary. I just
flew in back to Albuquerque just a few
hours ago, so it's been a little tiring.
But, it was an exciting event
and there are some things I'd like to
share with you about radionics. Let
me start by saying this. You can read a
bit about radionics in The Roots of
Consciousness, and I'm linking now to the
page. It has to do with folklore in The
Roots of Consciousness, folklore relating
to healing. But, my mentor Arthur M. Young,
who is the inventor of the Bell
Helicopter was a big enthusiast of
radionics. You know, after he invented the
Model 47, the very first commercially
licensed helicopter that was released in
1947, he began an exploration of all
sorts of fringe phenomena. He wasn't
really restricting himself by popular
belief because if people thought
something was quackery, and radionics has
been widely viewed as quackery, that
didn't stop him from making his own
investigations. He was convinced that
even though the radionics machines
seem to have no logical basis that he
could figure out, I mean there were wires
inside of these machines that weren't
even connected, he thought it was quite
legitimate. Although, he really thought it
was like training wheels.
He studied radionics practitioners like
Ruth Drown and Frances Farrelly, Frances
Farrelly in particular, widely respected
for her work in radionics. But, she
claimed eventually that the
radionics devices were like training
wheels. After she learned to work
with the device then she could perform
the same sorts of functions without
it. But I think what this is is for some
people who might have latent
psychokinetic abilities, however they
don't trust themselves enough. If
they're told, well there's a scientific
basis to all of this, you're not really
doing it, it has to do with Pythagorean
mathematical relationships and Tesla
scalar waves and other things, so they
don't have to feel responsible for it,
then it seems to work well for
individuals like this. Arthur Young once
described to me, and it's not in the book,
but he described an experiment he did
where radionics was used to rid a crop
of pests. The radionics practitioners
took a photograph of that crop and he
marked every other row, I don't know
maybe it was alfalfa for example.
According to Arthur Young, who said he
investigated this, was able to eliminate
pests, insects, from every other row of
this field using the radionics
instrument. You'll read in The Roots
of Consciousness, if you read that
section about Ruth Drown and her camera
and Arthur Young's test of the camera,
well, the camera worked without light at
all. She put film inside of a black box.
He had a toothache and when the film
was developed there was a picture of his
tooth. As I say, no lenses, no light.
Then he decided to test it again. He
used his finger. He pressed on his tooth
and when they took the next photo it was
an enlargement of the same tooth. When he
pressed on it of course, because he had
a toothache, the pain increased.Well,
those things impressed him a lot and at
the radionics conference - I call it the
radionics conference, it was the
Psychotronics conference - and at that
conference there were many different
vendors of radionics devices and
radionics
equipment and all modern, computerized,
the latest updated equipment. It was
quite impressive. I'm going to show you
some photographs of some of this
equipment to give you an idea of what
I'm talking about. It really has the
veneer of something very scientific, very
technologic, but the way it's used, I
think, it's actually like a recipe for a
magical ritual with the trappings of
science. Now, I happened to sit at
a luncheon table just yesterday with a
fellow who told me he was an engineer
and he happened on a radionics device.
Somebody sent it to him because they
said they found it in the attic or
something and didn't know what to do
with it and he's an engineer and they
sent it to him and he began studying it
to see what it was all about. I can tell
you that the history of radionics goes
back about a hundred years. The field was
basicallyâ€¦ The founder is said to be Dr.
Albert Abrams, who was a professor of
medicine at Stanford University. Even
though today it's largely regarded as
quackery, Abrams himself was a highly
credentialed individual. Now, this
engineer who sat next to me at lunch
wasn't a vendor. He was just sharing with
me his own personal experiences and he
said he'd learned by contacting the
various radionics associations. They have
conferences I think every year in Rapid
City, South Dakota. He attended those
conferences and began to get training
on the use of the device and he had a mentor
with whom he worked and he told me that
he used it actually to recover money
that was owed to him. Somebody had
borrowed a large sum of money from him
and after 10 years the fellow hadn't
paid
him back but in the meantime had bought
himself a new car and a new house and
seemed to be prospering. So he
used, you could say he engaged, in a
magical ritual really, to get the money
back. But, it was all done with radionics
equipment and as I say, the veneer of
science and technology. The idea is
you find just the right frequency to
solve the problem that you need. You use
the radionics equipment to broadcast
that frequency or to charge objects with
that frequency. So, radionics
practitioners will sell a variety of
jewelry supposedly charged with
different frequencies that are used for
different purposes. Now, he did this. His
mentor said, "Yes, you can do this."
He developed a frequency broadcasting to
the man who owed him money. Within a
few days, I think he said the first
time it took two weeks, and the fellow
who owed him the money called him up and
he said, "You know, I've been feeling
really guilty, I haven't paid you back
for so long." He said, "I couldn't sleep all
last night because of it. I felt so
guilty. And I want to start making
monthly payments." The monthly
payments came in and it was quite
satisfactory, but after about four months,
the monthly payments stopped. So,
according to the gentleman who sat
with me at the luncheon table, he said
that what had happened was, he decided to
use the radionics device for something
else and the setup that he had only
enabled him to work on one project at a
time. So, he had stopped focusing the
frequency on this individual. So
consulting with his mentor he switched
over again and began with the radionics
device, transmitting the psychokinetic
frequency, that's what I'll call it,
[because] I think it's really
psychokinesis.
The radionics device was again tuned
to this individual who owed money.
Within a couple of days, he called again
and he said, "I couldn't sleep again.
I'm so sorry I missed the payment. I'm
just going to send you the entire amount
of money I owe you all at once." And that
happened. So, here's what I have to say, to
the best of my knowledge, that
information that I have just shared with
you really belongs in the category of
folklore, because, you know, it wasn't
well attested. It was one person's
account to me of his experience. I have
no reason to disbelieve him, but on the
other hand I can't say that it was the
sort of thing that would stand up in a
courtroom, certainly not the sort of
thing that was tested in a double-blind
scientific experiment. But I do think
that it suggests to me people should be
looking into this. Probably there are, I
would imagine that if you dug into it,
you would find a few scientific studies,
because I know there are various
credentialed doctors who are using this.
It supposedly can heal a wide variety of
conditions as well as all sorts of other
psychokinetic projects. I wouldn't be
surprised if people use it for weather
control and who knows what else, because
there are several companies
manufacturing these devices to the best
of my knowledge. There must be hundreds
of practitioners and I'll bet you
could find various sources, different
books and scientific studies. As far
as Abrams, who was, as I say a Stanford
University professor, he died in 1924,
incidentally - I would imagine if one
dug back historically one would find
some scientific studies.
Surely, a Stanford University professor
would have wanted that. Although
the state of the art of science back in
the 1920s was not at all what it is
today. So, I'm sharing this with you
because I think that it's very
interesting that if you put the
trappings of modern science on top of
ancient magical practices in today's
environment where the scientists are, you
might say the high priest of our
culture, that it has a kind of, you could
call it a hypnotic effect, or a social,
cultural effect, that there's a
category of individuals, maybe typically
people who are trained as engineers and
scientists, who are not going to feel
comfortable doing something if they
thought it was simply a magical ritual.
But, if it at least has the trappings of
science, that enables them to feel
emotionally comfortable and to my way of
thinking, activates their psychokinesis.
Now, of course this is all speculative,
but what does this mean for you? I
guess the question you might wish to ask
yourself is that would you feel more
comfortable performing healings,
performing actions, causing things
to manifest in the universe, if you were
under the impression that you were
following a scientific protocol? Would
that make a difference to you? I think
for many people, in fact, it would. I don't
think radionics is for everybody but
it does seem, from the reports that I
have been hearing, that for certain
individuals, nerds, you might say, nerdy
type of people, that this
is a pathway to opening up latent
abilities. Perhaps like Frances
Farrelly you will graduate to the point
where you don't really need the
equipment any longer, the training wheels
so to speak. But maybe not. I think for
some people they're comfortable with
this equipment and they stick with it.
Probably like almost everything in
the field of parapsychology and the
behavioral sciences in general, it will
be statistical. It won't work a hundred
percent of the time. It may work 60,
70, 80 percent of the time, which isn't
bad at all. So, give it some thought and
once again, thank you for being with me.
